–1507","Aft 1441":"after 1441","1482":"1482","1460":"1460","Abt 1506":"about 1506","1448":"1448","1525":"1525","1435":"1435","1400":"1400","Abt 1430":"about 1430","1475":"1475","1441":"1441","1430":"1430","about 1464":"about 1464","1507":"1507","1506":"1506","about 1460":"about 1460","1416":"1416","Winnington, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Winnington, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Winnington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: (i) locative name from Winnington (Cheshire, Staffs). (ii)  see  Wennington  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wennington","meanings":["English: (i) locative name from Wennington (Hunts, Essex). (ii)  see  Winnington  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Winnington I was born about 1430, in Winnington, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Winnington, was 32 and his mother, Katherine de Venables, was 15. He married Catherine Grosvenor about 1464, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died about 1506, in his hometown, at the age of 78."},"et":{"Abt 1430–Abt 1506":"umbes 1430–umbes 1506","1430–1506":"1430–1506","1435–1506":"1435–1506","1448–1482":"1448–1482","1460–Female":"1460–Surnud","1475–1525":"1475–1525","1400–1441":"1400–1441","1416–1507":"1416–1507","Aft 1441":"pärast 1441","1482":"1482","1460":"1460","Abt 1506":"umbes 1506","1448":"1448","1525":"1525","1435":"1435","1400":"1400","Abt 1430":"umbes 1430","1475":"1475","1441":"1441","1430":"1430","about 1464":"umbes 1464","1507":"1507","1506":"1506","about 1460":"umbes 1460","1416":"1416","Winnington, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Winnington, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1430–Abt 1506":"noin 1430–noin 1506","1430–1506":"1430–1506","1435–1506":"1435–1506","1448–1482":"1448–1482","1460–Female":"1460–Kuollut","1475–1525":"1475–1525","1400–1441":"1400–1441","1416–1507":"1416–1507","Aft 1441":"1441 jälkeen","1482":"1482","1460":"1460","Abt 1506":"noin 1506","1448":"1448","1525":"1525","1435":"1435","1400":"1400","Abt 1430":"noin 1430","1475